<p>The <strong>Universal Approximation Theorem</strong> is a key result in machine learning stating that neural networks can approximate any continuous function to arbitrary accuracy, given sufficient size. (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_approximation_theorem?utm_source=chatgpt.com" title="Universal approximation theorem">Wikipedia</a>)</p>

<p>In its most common form, the theorem applies to feedforward networks with a single hidden layer. If the activation function is non-polynomial (like sigmoid or ReLU), the network can act as a “universal approximator” by increasing its width. (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_approximation_theorem?utm_source=chatgpt.com" title="Universal approximation theorem">Wikipedia</a>)</p>

<p>However, this is an existence result—it guarantees such a network exists, but does not explain how to find or train it effectively. (<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Universal_approximation_theorem?utm_source=chatgpt.com" title="Universal approximation theorem">Wikipedia</a>)</p>

